<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - world]]></title><link/> https://www.wsj.com/news/world <atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/wsj/en-us/world" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - world - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 7 月 20 日星期四 06:56:03 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[Two Killed in New Zealand Shooting on Eve of Women’s World Cup]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>当局表示，枪手也在建筑工地事件中死亡，另有几人受伤<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001068822"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820475?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">奥克兰枪击事件发生后，全副武装的新西兰警察站在中央商务区的路障前。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：艾比·帕尔/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001068822"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/mike-cherney" itemprop="url" rel="author">Mike Cherney</a></span> （悉尼）和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/rachel-bachman" itemprop="url" rel="author">Rachel Bachman</a></span> （奥克兰）</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 20 日上午 1:52（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/two-killed-in-new-zealand-shooting-on-eve-of-womens-world-cup-763abad5"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>悉尼——就在新西兰准备共同主办<a href="https://www.wsj.com/sports/soccer/womens-world-cup-us-national-team-348f2240?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">女足世界杯</a>之际，新西兰最大城市发生枪击事件，造成两人死亡，不过当局表示风险已得到控制，赛事将如期进行。</p><p>官员称，周四早上，一名枪手进入奥克兰市中心一栋正在建设的建筑并开枪。枪手在与警方交火后也当场死亡。包括一名警察在内的多人受伤。</p><p>当局表示，这起事件似乎与世界杯无关。新西兰警察局长安德鲁·科斯特表示，这名24岁的枪手在现场工作，枪击事件似乎与工作场所有关。</p><p>科斯特表示，他对这项赛事的安全性没有任何担忧，这项赛事由 32 支球队与澳大利亚共同主办。官员们表示，周四晚上挪威队与新西兰队在奥克兰举行的揭幕战将继续进行。</p><p> “这是一个总体上安全的国家，我们对为这次活动所做的准备工作感到非常自豪，”科斯特说。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820483?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">枪击事件后，建筑工人离开中央商务区。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Jason Oxenham/新西兰先驱报/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>新西兰总理克里斯·希普金斯表示，枪击事件似乎没有政治或意识形态动机，也不存在国家安全风险。</p><p> “显然，这对我们来说是一个非常严峻的早晨，”希普金斯说。 “但我们致力于举办这次比赛。这里不存在持续的风险。”</p><p>对于最近抵达枪支暴力相对较少的新西兰的足球队来说，周四早上的情况令人困惑。住宿在枪击现场附近的挪威队的许多球员都已经睡着了，被酒店窗外盘旋的直升机和街上大量的急救车辆吵醒。</p><p> “起初我们不知道发生了什么事，但最终电视和当地媒体有了最新消息，”挪威队队长马伦·米耶德在一份声明中说。她说，尽管如此，团队自始至终都感到安全。</p><p>美国女队发言人表示，所有球员均已安全，球队正在按照日常日程进行。新西兰官员表示，其他队伍都留在枪击现场附近，但一切都很安全。</p><p>足球管理机构国际足联表示，它一直就这起事件与各球队保持联系，事件始于当地时间周四上午 7 点 22 分左右，枪手进入大楼并开枪。警方称，枪手穿过大楼，开枪，最终将自己锁在电梯井里。与警方交枪后，罪犯被发现死亡。</p><p>现场视频显示，全副武装的警察在街道上奔跑。警方称，事件发生期间，一些工人不得不在大楼内避难。</p><p>科斯特表示，警方仍在努力确定枪手的死因。警方称，被枪手枪击的受伤警官被送往医院，情况危急，但目前病情已经稳定。警方称，其他人的伤势从中度到重度不等。救护车官员表示，七名因枪伤而受伤的人已接受治疗。</p><p>科斯特说，这名罪犯有家庭暴力史，被判处家庭拘留，并且没有使用猎枪的许可证。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/first-timeline-new-zealand-shooter-was-active-for-more-than-30-minutes-11552720064?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">2019 年基督城两座清真寺发生</a>枪击事件，造成 51 人死亡后<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/new-zealand-to-ban-military-style-semiautomatic-weapons-and-assault-rifles-11553134883?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，新西兰收紧了枪支法</a>，包括禁止大多数半自动武器。枪手澳大利亚人布伦顿·塔兰特被判处终身监禁，不得假释。官员认为枪击事件是恐怖袭击。</p><p>希普金斯说，周四枪击事件中使用的枪是泵动式霰弹枪。一些泵动式霰弹枪在枪支法的修改中也被禁止，但希普金斯无法透露所使用的武器是否属于禁止类别。科斯特后来说，枪支并未被禁止。</p><p>科斯特说：“对于那些来上班却发现自己陷入武装紧急情况的人来说，这是一起令人震惊和痛苦的事件。” “值得庆幸的是，许多人能够逃离大楼，但我知道对于那些躲藏或被困的人来说，这是一次可怕的经历。”</p><p>写信给 Mike Cherney <a href="mailto:mike.cherney@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">(mike.cherney@wsj.com)</a>和 Rachel Bachman ( <a href="mailto:Rachel.Bachman@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Rachel.Bachman@wsj.com)</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 20 Jul 2023 05:52:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/two-killed-in-new-zealand-shooting-on-eve-of-womens-world-cup-763abad5</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/two-killed-in-new-zealand-shooting-on-eve-of-womens-world-cup-763abad5<author><![CDATA[Mike CherneyRachel Bachman]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>横冲直撞/连环杀人</category><category>凶杀案</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>足球</category><category>运动的</category><category>恐怖主义</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>日常新闻</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>克里斯·希普金斯</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>横冲直撞</category><category>连环杀人案</category><category>凶杀案</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>足球</category><category>运动的</category><category>恐怖主义</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>常规新闻</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Summer China Fell Out of Love With Hollywood]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>中国观众更喜欢国产电影，而不是好莱坞电影<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001066055"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820122?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">汤姆·克鲁斯的新片《碟中谍》等一些好莱坞夏季影片在中国的票房表现一直疲弱。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：CFOTO/Future Publishing/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001066055"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/erich-schwartzel" itemprop="url" rel="author">埃里希·施瓦策尔</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/rachel-liang" itemprop="url" rel="author">雷切尔·梁</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 20 日上午 12:06（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/not-even-tom-cruise-can-charm-chinas-moviegoers-into-seeing-hollywood-films-49d39f3a"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>在过去的十年里，居住在上海的退休人员方方逐渐熟悉了好莱坞最大的出口产品：詹姆斯·邦德。汤姆·克鲁斯。 《速度与激情》剧组。</p><p>但最近，方发现在他自己的国家制作的电影比美国提供的电影更有吸引力。</p><p> “现在的好莱坞电影越来越无稽之谈，”60 岁的方本周在上海一家电影院的大厅里说道。 “像蜘蛛侠和美国队长这样的超级英雄太肤浅了，我什至不会在 IMAX 3-D 中观看他们。”</p><p>方和数百万其他中国电影观众正在迫使好莱坞高管面对一个令人震惊的新现实：曾经拥抱他们电影的国家现在正在远离他们。今年夏天对美国娱乐业在全球第二大市场来说是一场大屠杀，巩固了中国消费者多年来<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ant-man-gets-squashed-as-hong-kongs-movie-revival-follows-covid-protests-6f466922?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">对国产电影的</a>吸引力。</p><p>根据 Artisan Gateway 的数据，今年前 6 个月，美国电影在中国的总票房达到 5.92 亿美元，低于 2019 年上半年的 19 亿美元，而前一年， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-problem-plaguing-movies-concerts-and-casinos-chinas-out-of-reach-spender-11661333405?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Covid-19 限制措施导致了观影活动陷入瘫痪</a>。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="1066" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/4cf2f516-1031-4a0a-b2a0-5d532217bb88-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> 2021 年和 2022 年，有两部美国电影跻身中国电影票房前十，但今年迄今为止只有一部进入前十。与 2014 年到 2018 年相比，这是一个显着的变化，当时美国电影在每年中国上映的前 10 部影片中至少占据 3 部，甚至占据了 10 部影片中的 5 部。</p><p> 14 亿中国人口味的转变<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-chinas-growing-clout-led-hollywood-to-look-for-a-new-villain-11644037244?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，对那些已经越来越依赖票房收入的好莱坞电影公司和中国领导人产生了相当大的影响</a>，他们长期以来一直将影院视为通过文化信息影响民众的场所。</p><p>与这些备受瞩目的电影曾经在中国的票房收入相比，一些夏季上映的票房收入是灾难性的。根据中国票务公司猫眼的数据，截至 7 月 18 日，<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/DIS" class="">华特迪士尼</a><span class="company-name-type">公司的</span>《 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/indiana-jones-and-the-dial-of-destiny-review-harrison-ford-and-fools-gold-c209a7fb?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">夺宝奇兵</a>》的票房收入为 330 万美元，与丹麦的票房收入大致相同。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/elemental-struggles-on-opening-weekend-the-flash-also-flat-36f5789b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">动画寓言片《元素》</a>在中国票房收入为 1,560 万美元，仅次于墨西哥。</p><p>上周末，《 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tom-cruises-new-mission-impossible-falls-short-of-other-summer-hits-a6a6f054?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">碟中谍6：航位推算</a>》在中国的首映票房为 2,540 万美元，比 2018 年上映的上一部影片低 66%。有两部中国电影领先于动作片位居榜首。</p><p>一位高管警告说，如果票房收入继续保持在如此低的水平，制片厂可能会认为不值得提交电影在中国上映。</p><p>迄今为止，很少有电影能像迪士尼的《 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-little-mermaid-review-disney-halle-baily-remake-melissa-mccarthy-javier-bardem-63ce209c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">小美人鱼</a>》那样乏善可陈，自 5 月底以来，该片的票房收入已达 370 万美元，与智利（人口：1,950 万）在世界上人口最多的国家之一的票房表现不相上下。 ）。在中国社交媒体和上海影院，一些电影观众表示不愿意看一部由黑人女演员扮演爱丽儿的电影。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="289" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819307?width=700&amp;height=289" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">迪士尼的《夺宝奇兵》在中国的票房收入为 330 万美元，与丹麦的票房收入大致相同。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：沃尔特·迪士尼/埃弗雷特收藏</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>“《小美人鱼》过于注重政治正确性，”40 多岁的上海自由职业者周说。 “我去电影院是为了娱乐，而不是为了被灌输某些价值观。”</p><p>随着观影人数减少，电影公司在中国营销电影的费用也随之减少，从而引发了低宣传导致低兴趣的恶性循环，反之亦然。</p><p>当好莱坞电影在20世纪90年代首次进入中国时，它们为好奇的中国观众提供了了解西方生活的机会。 《泰坦尼克号》、《阿凡达》等大片售出了价值数亿美元的门票。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/global-boundaries-break-down-for-movies-in-u-s-and-china-11571863144?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">中国的票房稳步增长</a>，而美国的电影票房却停滞不前，导致电影公司高管优先考虑吸引观众的电影，并得到了中国政府审查机构的批准， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/disney-gets-boost-as-china-clears-marvel-superhero-films-for-release-11674026977?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">每部影片在上映前都必须进行审查，</a>找出任何令人反感的情节点。在中国剧院。</p><p>不久前，好莱坞最重要的系列电影还经常从中国的影院获得数亿美元的收入。现在，他们的受欢迎程度正在下降。</p><p> 《变形金刚：绝迹重生》2014 年的票房收入超过 3 亿美元，但新版《变形金刚》仅占其中的三分之一。 《速度与激情8》2017 年的票房收入超过 3.48 亿美元，但最新一期的票房收入已降至 1.2 亿美元。两年后，漫威影业的精彩影片《复仇者联盟：终局之战》以 6.291 亿美元成为中国历史上票房最高的美国电影；该工作室的最新版本“银河护卫队卷。 《3》的票房还没有突破1亿美元。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819829?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>当可口可乐、耐克和 iPhone 在中国不再稀缺时，“我们对好莱坞电影不再抱有幻想”，家住中国东北山东省省会济南的 39 岁工程师冯念强说。 。</p><p>相反，中国观众推动了本土电影的票房大片，例如《流浪地球2》，该片讲述了一群英雄的中国宇航员拯救地球的故事，票房收入超过5亿美元。中国惊悚片《迷失星辰》票房收入超过 4 亿美元。</p><p>中国的票房也受到当局认可的宣传片的提振，例如去年的《长津湖之战2》，这是中国有史以来票房最高的电影的续集。它讲述了朝鲜战争期间中国军队与美国军队作战的故事——电影制片人在两国关系紧张时探索了这个故事情节。</p><p> “讲述我们自己故事的中国电影肯定会更能引起我们的共鸣，”28 岁的钟志鹏说，他每两周就会去上海公寓附近的电影院。</p><p>放映全球大片的娱乐技术公司 IMAX 的首席执行官理查德·格尔方德 (Richard Gelfond) 表示，中国当局似乎致力于帮助中国影院从 Covid-19 疫情导致的电影放映封锁中恢复过来。去年，只有25部外国电影获准在中国上映。今年已经超过了这个数字。</p><p> “他们放了更多的好莱坞电影，”格尔方德在接受采访时说。 “感觉就像平常的一年。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="415" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819310?width=700&amp;height=415" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">中国电影观众推动了《流浪地球2》等本土影片的票房大卖。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：CFOTO/Future Publishing/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>今年早些时候，IMAX 在农历新年期间创下了有史以来最高的票房成绩，农历新年是中国最受欢迎的观影时间。截至 7 月 9 日的本季度，该公司大中华区票房为 850 万美元，仅比美国和加拿大票房低 60 万美元左右。</p><p>然而，一旦进入中国，电影公司就必须应对经济逆风，包括<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-problem-that-wont-go-away-in-china-high-youth-unemployment-f22e3b8c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">中国 16 岁至 24 岁人群的城镇失业率</a>上个月飙升至 21.3%，几乎是 2019 年初失业率的两倍。</p><p>由于制造业陷入困境以及西方加息侵蚀了消费者支出，该<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-economy-barely-grows-as-recovery-fades-5652a92a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">国整体经济</a>正面临通货紧缩。</p><p>某些方面有理由感到乐观。 8 月，杀人鲨续集《巨齿鲨 2：海沟》将作为罕见的中美合拍片上映，融资、​​选角和其他制作决策将由两国分担。</p><p>为了吸引那些希望在银幕上看到自己国家形象的中国电影观众，制片人贝尔·艾弗里游说让《战狼2》等民族主义大片中的中国明星吴京担任主角。 “对于中国来说，他代表了典型的中国男人，”她说。 “忠诚的战士，伟大的父亲。”</p><p>吴扮演一位科学家，游说研究和了解在水下造成严重破坏的巨型鲨鱼——艾弗里说，这反映了东方与自然的和谐——而杰森·斯坦森扮演的西方同行则认为他们应该杀死它。</p><p>艾弗里表示，通过将中国明星和主题融入电影中，《巨齿鲨2》避免了电影公司在期待中国观众简单出现时陷入的陷阱。</p><p> “仅仅认为自己最了解的傲慢态度——那些日子已经结束了，”她说。</p><p class="articleTagLine"> ——上海的赵跃岭对本文有贡献。</p><p>写信给 Erich Schwartzel <a href="mailto:erich.schwartzel@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">（erich.schwartzel@wsj.com）</a>和 Rachel Liang（ <a href="mailto:rachel.liang@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">rachel.liang@wsj.com</a> ）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 20 Jul 2023 04:06:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/not-even-tom-cruise-can-charm-chinas-moviegoers-into-seeing-hollywood-films-49d39f3a</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/not-even-tom-cruise-can-charm-chinas-moviegoers-into-seeing-hollywood-films-49d39f3a<author><![CDATA[Erich SchwartzelRachel Liang]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>gfx-contrib</category><category>视听制作</category><category>电影制作</category><category>电影发行</category><category>电影/影像展览</category><category>媒体内容分发</category><category>休闲/艺术/酒店</category><category>媒体/娱乐</category><category>动画电影</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>名人</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>故事片</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>电影</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>动画电影</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>名人</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>故事片</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category><category>电影</category><category>视听制作</category><category>电影院电影制作</category><category>电影院电影发行</category><category>电影</category><category>影像展览</category><category>媒体内容分发</category><category>闲暇</category><category>款待</category><category>媒体</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Pivotal Mission in Ukraine’s Counteroffensive: Hunting for Mines]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>事实证明，地雷是基辅缓慢反攻的最大挑战之一<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819475/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="乌克兰南部新瓦西利夫卡附近，一名乌克兰军人在用作临时基地的房屋内组装金属探测器。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>乌克兰南部新瓦西利夫卡附近，一名乌克兰军人在用作临时基地的房屋内组装金属探测器。 <span></span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001065730"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001065730"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/isabel-coles" itemprop="url" rel="author">Isabel Coles</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name">Ievgeniia Sivorka Emanuele Satolli 为《华尔街日报》拍摄的照片</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 20 日上午 12:05（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-pivotal-mission-in-ukraines-counteroffensive-hunting-for-mines-78197558"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>乌克兰巴哈蒂尔——乌克兰士兵在漆黑中出发，偷偷穿过炮弹坑坑洼洼的田野，执行反攻中最重要的任务之一，也是最危险的任务之一。</p><p>战斗工程师（被称为工兵）配备金属探测器、铲子和抓钩， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-adopts-slow-approach-to-counteroffensive-our-problem-everywhere-is-the-sky-a2e51d7a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">与俄罗斯军队一起沿着前线</a>寻找地雷，同时努力不被附近敌人发现。</p><p> “你不能紧张，”一位呼号为“渔夫”的 49 岁工兵说道，他领导着乌克兰第 68 猎兵旅的 50 人小组。</p><p>六月初，乌克兰军队使用西方捐赠的坦克和其他装甲车进行的初步推进在俄罗斯雷区沉没，之后乌克兰军队求助于费舍曼这样的人来扫清前进的道路。</p><p>在西方军队训练和装备基辅部队发动进攻的几个月里，俄罗斯建造了一些自世界大战以来最广泛的战场防御工事。乌克兰总统泽伦斯基哀叹西方盟友行动不够迅速，让俄罗斯有时间在比加州还大的地区布雷。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819477?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> “你不能紧张，”49 岁的工兵费舍曼说。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>尽管面临挑战，乌克兰<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-war-counteroffensive-frontlines-russia-add3e4e4?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">自六周多前开始反攻以来</a>夺回的领土比俄罗斯在相同个月内夺取的领土还要多。基辅尚未将其所有部队投入战斗，保留了一些受过西方训练的部队来利用俄罗斯防御的任何突破口。</p><p>但进展速度比乌克兰和西方官员所希望的要慢，俄罗斯的主要防线仍然在前面——布满反坦克和杀伤人员地雷的田野、混凝土加固的战壕、铁丝网、龙牙和反坦克沟渠。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>总部位于英国的皇家联合军种研究所智囊团在今年早些时候的一份报告中表示，工程已被证明是俄罗斯军队最强大的部门之一。包括地雷在内的障碍物旨在减缓乌克兰军队的速度，并将前进的步兵引导到俄罗斯攻击直升机、火炮和无人机可以拦截的位置。</p><p>一名乌克兰军官获得的一份 2023 年俄罗斯手册规定了使用地雷挫败乌克兰机械化纵队的指导方针。一些反坦克地雷将不加伪装地埋设，以将乌克兰军队转移到埋有隐藏地雷的地区。其他的则应在障碍物（例如故障车辆和被毁坏的道路）旁边成群种植，以诱捕试图绕过它们的乌克兰军队。</p><p>去年美国向乌克兰提供的价值6000万美元的军事援助中就包括扫雷设备。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          edgetoedge
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/09e46d1a-2d98-4a70-8257-bf1ff52a084c.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>其中的解决方案包括扫雷线装药，它会在雷区发射一枚装有炸药线的小型火箭，并引爆附近的任何地雷。乌克兰已经拥有苏联开发的同类产品。</p><p>据跟踪双方在战争中损失的独立分析小组 Oryx 称，芬兰向乌克兰提供的六辆 Leopard 2R 装甲扫雷车中的一辆在反攻初期被摧毁，两辆被损坏。</p><p>渔夫手机上的卫星图像显示了乌克兰军队所面临的情况：它显示了俄罗斯阵地前的五排反坦克地雷带。但在清理敌人的地雷之前，工兵必须在自己的地雷中打开一个缺口。</p><p>渔夫是一位狂热的钓鱼爱好者，他将自己的爱好与工作进行了比较，因为两者都涉及放置诱饵和等待捕获。他在 2015 年冲突的早期阶段与俄罗斯作战，但在去年全面入侵之前，他又回到建筑行业工作。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="2050" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/96ff07b0-8f9b-4a93-a4a1-8eac8dac9fcb-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>去年抵达武勒达尔附近的前线后，他的手下（自称“渔民”）开始在大约曼哈顿四分之一面积的区域埋设约 25,000 枚地雷。有时需要携带多枚反坦克地雷跋涉数英里，每枚重 22 磅。</p><p>渔民们埋下的地雷炸毁了俄罗斯第 155 海军步兵旅，在一次失败的冬季攻势中挫败了对武勒达尔村周围的多次袭击。渔夫手机上的一段视频显示，三辆毫无防备的俄罗斯坦克沿着雪原上刻出的轨道排成一列前进。费舍曼说，敌方工兵此前已经清理了道路，但他的人在夜色掩护下再次布雷。视频显示，第一辆坦克滚过地雷，引发爆炸，促使车队的其他车辆掉头。</p><p>随着攻势迫在眉睫，渔民的任务是在不透露乌克兰军队打算攻击的地点的情况下，清理出一条穿过自己防御工事的道路。为了让敌人猜不透，工兵们从他们埋设的地雷中取出炸药，同时留下外壳作为诱饵。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819482?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">所谓的渔民的任务是在前线寻找地雷。 </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819481?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">一名工兵展示他如何探测并清除地面上的地雷。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>乌克兰军队在渔民前线取得了一些早期战术胜利，夺回了东部村庄布拉霍达特内。但是，和其他地方一样，地雷已被证明是一个大问题。有一次，乌克兰军队占领了俄罗斯阵地，却遭到猛烈炮火攻击。一名留着山羊胡、呼号为“布巴”的工兵说，他们在试图带着伤员撤退时触发了杀伤人员地雷。</p><p> “当我们进入被占领土时，我们是盲目的，”布巴说。</p><p>工兵们戴着夜视镜，用金属探测器扫描前方的地面。有时，他们距离俄罗斯阵地如此之近，以至于可以听到敌人的声音。当金属探测器收到信号时，它们会探测地球以确定地下有什么。没有紧张的余地。 “你的手不能颤抖，”渔夫说道，他穿着一件印有“晚上好，我们来自乌克兰”的 T 恤。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="922" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/02c9bc6f-0429-45df-9c7f-077f6a8a6db3-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>检测到的金属通常是无害的弹片，散落在乌克兰南部前线沿线的田野上。但如果是地雷，工兵们会用短柄铲子将其揭开，然后用绳子系上抓钩。</p><p>他们在安全距离外拉动绳索，以拆除反坦克地雷。俄罗斯军队经常在其下方埋设杀伤人员地雷，当反坦克地雷被拆除时就会触发。 “风险总是存在的，”布巴说。</p><p>绊网在黑暗中是看不见的，因此工兵有时会等到黎明才出去寻找它们。费舍曼说，为此，最好的工具是簧片：拉紧但屈服强度足以不会触发绊线。 “没有人想出比这更好的工具，”他一边说，一边从流经的河岸上拔下一根芦苇。这些人当时正在执行前线任务，暂时休息，住在一间空房子里，等待进一步的命令。</p><p>费舍曼说，工兵的预期寿命很短。尽管如此，他说到目前为止他还没有因地雷而丧生。他认为这是他最大的成就。</p><p> “我来这里不是为了成为英雄，”他说。 “我来这里只是为了完成我的工作：赢得战争。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819480?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">工兵在前往另一个地点之前准备并打包他们的设备。 </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819474?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">渔夫说，没有在地雷中失去一个人是他最大的成就。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>写信给 Isabel Coles，邮箱为<a href="mailto:isabel.coles@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">isabel.coles@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 20 Jul 2023 04:05:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-pivotal-mission-in-ukraines-counteroffective-hunting-for-mines-78197558</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-pivotal-mission-in-ukraines-counteroffective-hunting-for-mines-78197558<author><![CDATA[Isabel Coles]]></author><category> gfx-contrib</category><category>乌克兰</category><category>华尔街日报</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>武装部队</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>乌克兰</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>武装部队</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Political Rise of Ultra-Orthodox Jews Shakes Israel’s Sense of Identity]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>快速增长的宗教保守派团体与内塔尼亚胡结盟，挑战最高法院，引发大规模抗议运动；义务兵役制成为一个关键问题<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-816908/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="布内布拉克 (Bnei Brak) 聚集了大量极端正统的犹太人，被称为正统派 (Haredim)。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>布内布拉克 (Bnei Brak) 聚集了大量极端正统的犹太人，被称为正统派 (Haredim)。 <span></span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001067629"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001067629"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dov-lieber" itemprop="url" rel="author">Dov Lieber</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/shayndi-raice" itemprop="url" rel="author">Shayndi Raice</a></span> / 摄影：Kobi Wolf 为《华尔街日报》拍摄</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 20 日上午 12:01 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-ultra-orthodox-haredim-military-service-supreme-court-of-ultra-orthodox-jews-shakes-israels-sense-of-identity-b3155e01"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>以色列伯内布拉克——自以色列建国以来，犹太以色列人的义务兵役被广泛接受为分裂社会中的团结力量。</p><p>现在这个问题有可能导致国家分裂。以色列的极端正统犹太人是一个快速发展且强大的政治集团，长期以来一直回避服兵役以及世俗社会的其他方面。他们<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-israel-army-service-is-required-for-all-that-could-now-change-2c76624d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">争取永久免役的努力</a>多次被以色列最高法院挫败。他们与总理本杰明·内塔尼亚胡领导的利库德集团结盟，推动<a href="https://www.wsj.com/story/why-israelis-are-protesting-netanyahu-governments-judicial-overhaul-0933acc5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">司法改革，以削弱法院的力量</a>。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-protests-flare-up-in-new-push-to-stop-judicial-overhaul-9f939aac?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">改革的第一部分引发了大规模抗议活动，连续 28 周震撼以色列</a>，预计最早将于周日获得以色列议会批准。</p><p>这场冲突触及以色列固有身份问题的核心：它是现代自由民主国家还是由宗教定义的社会？许多世俗的以色列人将司法改革视为增强那些利用宗教来削弱基本公民权利的人的权力的一步。</p><p> “世俗社会想要一个完整的现代国家，”耶路撒冷智库以色列民主研究所的学者吉拉德·马拉赫说。 “极端正统派的目标是建立一个强大的宗教社会。”</p><p>极端正统的犹太人，如叶霍舒亚·梅努钦 (Yehoshua Menuchin)，40 岁了，有妻子、六个儿子，没有稳定的工作，他称自己为正统派，意思是那些在上帝面前颤抖的人。许多正统派男人不定期工作，而是选择在称为犹太学校的宗教神学院学习神圣文本。他们认为，他们通过保留犹太传统并为以色列提供神圣保护，以自己的方式为国家做出贡献。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-816909?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">布内布拉克 (Bnei Brak) 的一所犹太学校，男人们在那里领取津贴来学习宗教文献。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “我认为我们做出的牺牲丝毫不减，”梅努钦说。 “我已经传承了这个世界的乐趣。我已经放弃了餐馆、电影院、俱乐部。我一生中已经放弃了很多东西。”</p><p>以色列社会的一个元素梅努钦和许多其他正统派人士都回避的是义务兵役，这是以色列主流社会的一种成人仪式。大多数犹太男女从 18 岁开始都会在军队服役两到三年。在军队中建立的友谊也可以作为军旅生活后职业联系的基础。</p><p>以色列最高法院曾两次否决旨在正式将正统派排除在征兵之外的立法，最近一次是在 2017 年，理由是该立法造成了公民的不平等待遇。法院已允许临时豁免，以便政府找到解决方案。</p><p>这些决定加剧了宗教保守派与最高法院之间的摩擦，最高法院<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-judge-at-the-heart-of-israels-constitutional-crisis-de698670?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">长期以来一直是个人自由的坚定捍卫者</a>，维护以色列阿拉伯公民、妇女和 LGBTQ 群体的权利。</p><p>正统派现在拥有反击的政治影响力。他们的两个政党——一个代表欧洲血统的犹太人，另一个代表来自大中东的犹太人——组成了现任政府中仅次于利库德集团的第二大集团，在议会 160 个席位中拥有 18 个席位。他们是内塔尼亚胡掌控权力的关键，因为他的联盟总共只控制 64 个席位。他们经常威胁说，如果他们的各种要求得不到满足，他们就会离开联盟。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-816911?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">犹太东正教团体在 Ponevezh Yeshiva 学习。 </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-816912?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">议会中的正统派希望颁布立法，允许在某些公共场所将男女分开。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/video/series/in-depth-features/wsj-exclusive-an-interview-with-israeli-prime-minister-benjamin-netanyahu/D95FB00D-DFCE-4B6E-9B89-889EB0968CE4?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在接受《华尔街日报》采访时</a>，内塔尼亚胡称最高法院是“地球上最积极的司法法院”，并表示“以色列公众越来越认识到司法改革的必要性。”不过，他表示，他的目标是缓和一些最初的提议，而是“以谨慎的方式推进”。</p><p>政府希望彻底改革这一制度，并将更多权力交给民选官员。提案包括削弱法院推翻政府决定的能力，并赋予立法者在挑选新法官的委员会中的多数发言权。</p><p>来自世俗以色列人和一些温和宗教犹太人的强烈反对。</p><p> 3 月，51 岁的预备役中校罗恩·谢尔夫 (Ron Scherf) 帮助<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israeli-judicial-overhaul-pits-secular-religious-communities-against-each-other-a4177c16?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">组织了一次穿过以色列最大的正统派城市布内布拉克 (Bnei Brak) 的游行</a>。抗议者举着标语，敦促正统派参军。一些正统派向抗议者投掷传单，称他们永远不会在“叛教”军队中服役。”</p><p> “我们确实相信以色列的世俗和正统派之间需要签订新的合同，”舍夫说。 “如果目前的情况不改变，我认为以色列不可能作为一个自由、繁荣和强大的国家存在。”</p><p> “我们即将发生一场重大冲突，”受欢迎的正统派媒体人物伊斯雷尔·科恩反驳道。 “如果没有一方承担责任，事情的结局就不会好。” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1038" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/a57e9a71-225e-434e-b047-fcb1a5e45e4e-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>除了服兵役之外，许多以色列人认为正统的生活方式对该国未来的繁荣构成了直接威胁。大约一半的正统派男人不工作。相反，他们从事宗教研究，靠妻子的工资、慈善机构、政府补助和补贴生活。根据以色列中央统计局的数据，随着出生率稳步上升，目前每名女性生育 6.5 个孩子左右，而普通人口的生育率约为 3.0 个，据以色列中央统计局称，大约 130 万正统派占总人口的 13.3%。作为增长最快的群体，到 2065 年，他们将占以色列总人口的近三分之一。</p><p>正统派利用他们的政治权力扩大市政税收折扣、早期儿童保育补贴以及对低收入大家庭的租金援助——从技术上讲，所有以色列人都可以获得这些福利，但由于其人口特征，这些福利往往有利于正统派。据以色列民主研究所称，他们或他们的犹太学院还为约 14 万名全日制学习的正统男子提供津贴或助学金。该研究所由一位前中间派政治家领导，发现正统派家庭缴纳的税款比非正统派家庭少三分之一。</p><p>在 5 月份写给内塔尼亚胡的一封信中，超过 200 名以色列主要经济学家警告说， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-netanyahu-faces-pushback-over-plan-to-subsidize-ultra-orthodox-schools-45568a14?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">一项计划增加对拒绝教授世俗科目的正统教育机构的资助</a>，同时增加全日制托拉学习者的津贴，将使以色列转变为“ “第三世界”经济让正统儿童无法为今天的劳动力做好准备。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-816913?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Ponevezh Yeshiva 的外套和帽子。 </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-816916?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">一名男子在布内布拉克的一家旧衣店购物。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/israels-judicial-reforms-could-strengthen-religions-role-in-public-life-11674476463?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">正统派的目标是将宗教扩展到公共生活的更多领域</a>。自内塔尼亚胡去年重新掌权以来，他们通过了一项法律，允许医院在犹太节日逾越节期间禁止面包产品进入公立医院。他们还表示，希望颁布立法，允许在某些公共场所或正统派经常参加的活动中将男女分开，以色列律师普遍认为这是违宪的。</p><p>正统派已经在公共生活的许多方面拥有巨大的权力。他们控制着拉巴努特（Rabbanut），这是一个监督婚姻和离婚并决定谁是犹太人的政府机构。拉巴努特长期以来拒绝承认犹太教的任何非正统分支，这一直是一个紧张的问题，特别是在散居国外的犹太人中。他们还对著名的犹太圣地拥有管理控制权。</p><p>最近发生在布内布拉克的抗议活动让耶霍舒亚·梅努钦 (Yehoshua Menuchin) 的妻子德沃拉 (Dvora) 不为所动。 “抗议的人对犹太教一无所知，”她说。 “他们就像婴儿一样。如果他们了解犹太教，他们就不会这样做。”</p><p>她的社区拥挤、喧闹、活泼，行人（包括许多儿童）挤满了狭窄街道的人行道，街道两旁是神圣的书店和小餐馆，出售传统的东欧犹太食品，如 kugel、gefilte 鱼和 cholent。每个角落和每个公交车站旁都矗立着一排排的慈善箱，其中大部分最终将捐给犹太学院的学生及其家人。</p><p>梅努钦一家靠资助约书亚全日制学习的美国捐助者提供的资金、政府补贴、来自朋友或家人的无息贷款以及零工生活。德沃拉大部分时间都呆在家里做饭和打扫卫生，并用一台可以个性化圆顶小帽等犹太物品的机器赚点小钱。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-816914?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">行人在 Bnei Brak 过马路。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>梅纽钦在晚上进行宗教主题的讲座。有时他的听众会给他小额捐款。他还花很少的费用修理犹太教，比如护命匣，这是一种小皮盒，里面装有写有《托拉》文字的卷轴，犹太男子在晨祷时将其绑在头上和手臂上。</p><p>梅努钦一家住在一套三居室的公寓里，他们的六个男孩被分在两个房间里。他们所有的家具都是二手买的。</p><p>梅纽钦早上 7 点起得很早，穿着正统派男人穿的黑裤子和白衬衫参加晨祷。早餐后，他开车前往犹太学院，在那里他花了一天的时间主要学习《塔木德》，这是一部古老的犹太文本，是犹太法律的基础。</p><p>梅纽钦的犹太学校——名为 Kisay Rahamim，意为“仁慈之席”，主要服务于北非裔犹太人——要求他用电子卡刷卡进入，这样州政府就可以确认他确实每天都在学习。</p><p>梅努钦和他的孩子们在八年级后停止了所有世俗教育。他们不会读或说英语，而梅努钦只能做基本的加法和减法。他说这就是他度过一生所需要的一切。</p><p>耶路撒冷正统公共事务研究所所长拉比·伊莱·佩利 (Rabbi Eli Paley) 表示，学习托拉的生活方式造就了“好丈夫、好父亲、好社区成员和好志愿者”。</p><p> “那东西不值钱吗？”他说。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-816910?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">在 Bnei Brak 的街道上漫步。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>虽然经济学家表示，为犹太学院系统提供资金将使大多数正统派陷入贫困，但他们认为，他们对资本主义的激烈竞争不感兴趣，他们的生活方式让他们感到快乐和满足。</p><p> “如果你去游乐园，或者喝一杯酒，那一刻你会很高兴。但当你学习《托拉》时，快乐就会一直伴随着你，”梅努钦说。</p><p>写信给 Dov Lieber <a href="mailto:dov.lieber@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">（dov.lieber@wsj.com）</a>和 Shayndi Raice（ <a href="mailto:Shayndi.Raice@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Shayndi.Raice@wsj.com</a> ）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 20 Jul 2023 04:01:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-ultra-orthodox-haredim-military-service-supreme-court-of-ultra-orthodox-jews-shakes-israels-sense-of-identity-b3155e01</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/israel-ultra-orthodox-haredim-military-service-supreme-court-of-ultra-orthodox-jews-shakes-israels-sense-of-identity-b3155e01<author><![CDATA[Dov LieberShayndi Raice]]></author><category> gfx-contrib</category><category> photo-commission</category><category>领导者</category><category>华尔街日报</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>宗教</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>本杰明·内塔尼亚胡</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>宗教</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[A $6 Billion China-Built Railway Is on the Move With a Vast New Network Down the Track]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> People and investments flow into Laos, making it &#39;more like China&#39; <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817243/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="老挝琅勃拉邦当地人停止出售蘑菇，观看火车穿过湄公河上的一座新桥。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Locals stopped selling mushrooms to watch a train cross a new bridge over the Mekong River in Luang Prabang, Laos. <span></span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001062426"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001062426"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/feliz-solomon" itemprop="url" rel="author">Feliz Solomon</a></span> | Photographs by Lauren DeCicca for The Wall Street Journal</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated July 19, 2023 11:49 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-grand-vision-for-a-vast-rail-network-transforms-a-neighboring-country-17f067cc"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> BOTEN, Laos—A few years ago, this small town on the border with China was a few dusty lanes surrounded by tropical forests. Now, a nearly $6 billion Chinese-built railroad cuts through it—and a city is rising.</p><p> Dozens of half-constructed office towers and warehouses rise into the skyline. A Chinese developer, Yunnan Haicheng Industrial Group, is pitching the six-square-mile special economic zone where they stand as the gateway between China and Southeast Asia, a place where labor is cheap and exporting is easy, thanks to the new train.</p><p> Jackhammers clamor until nightfall, when they give way to the sounds of Chinese pop music blaring from open-air restaurants where transiting businessmen unwind over beer and spicy peanuts.</p><p> “There&#39;s a Chinese saying that when the whistle blows, it&#39;s worth 10,000 taels of gold,” said He Ming Jia, a senior executive at Yunnan Haicheng. “Chinese investment follows the train.”</p><p> Globally, China&#39;s now decade-old Belt and Road Initiative, or BRI, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-belt-road-debt-11663961638?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">has been in retreat</a> , with a number of projects stalled or mired in controversy—at times over allegations of incurring <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hidden-debt-plagues-chinas-belt-and-road-infrastructure-plan-studies-find-11632866461?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">unsustainable debts</a> for developing countries. But in this part of Southeast Asia, it is alive and kicking. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1068" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/eb4e2cde-13c0-46ec-8db3-1b38e1005f4b-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Beijing is casting the 262-mile rail line, which launched in late 2021, as a showcase of how its grand vision for <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/railroaded-the-chinese-high-speed-train-network-no-one-else-really-wants-1526644804?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">regionwide rail connectivity</a> can be transformative for the local economy. The plan imagines a China-backed network stretching through Southeast Asia&#39;s agricultural and industrial heartlands—drawing its neighbors into a tighter embrace and binding their economies to its own for decades to come.</p><p> “To China, this is a key mega project. Completion of this railway will demonstrate that BRI remains on track,” said Yu Hong, a senior research fellow at the East Asian Institute of the National University of Singapore. “This is very much the message that China wants to convey to the world.”</p><p> The Laos-China Railway is the first leg of Beijing&#39;s plan. It runs between the Chinese commercial hub of Kunming and Vientiane, the Lao capital near the border with Thailand. Beijing aims to extend it further south, linking to the Thai and Malaysian capitals, Bangkok and Kuala Lumpur.</p><p> China also plans to upgrade a railroad that runs east through Cambodia—and build another running west from Kunming to the coast of Myanmar. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818984?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Developers describe the nascent Boten Special Economic Zone in Laos as a new gateway between China and Southeast Asia. </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818988?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A worker in Laos inspects a cargo train headed for China.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Momentum in Laos, China hopes, will kick-start progress elsewhere. Construction is under way in Thailand and Malaysia, but has faced local skepticism and delays.</p><p> Thai transportation officials have said a section from Bangkok to the Lao border will be complete by 2028. Negotiations on upgrading an existing rail link between Bangkok and Kuala Lumpur are continuing. A China-built railroad connecting Malaysia&#39;s coasts is expected to be completed by the end of 2026, after years in limbo.</p><p> The World Bank has said the Laos-China Railway could raise the Southeast Asian country&#39;s aggregate income by up to 21% over the long term, if it is managed well. But <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/debt-troubles-in-laos-reveal-economic-turmoil-in-developing-world-11657877403?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">economists are still at odds</a> over its financial rationale.</p><p> Laos was already struggling to pay back lenders when it borrowed $1.54 billion from China&#39;s Export-Import Bank to fund its share. And it is unlikely to make much revenue from the train itself, owning only a 30% stake while three Chinese companies own the rest. According to the World Bank, the country&#39;s total debt has reached “critical levels,” around $14.5 billion in 2021, with China accounting for about half of its external debt. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=D53246B2-FCE2-4490-BA93-E459B9066FAE&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fchinas-grand-vision-for-a-vast-rail-network-transforms-a-neighboring-country-17f067cc&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> China has some of the fastest—and busiest—trains in the world. But despite having some of the same technology, the US has struggled to develop its own high-speed rail. WSJ explores the barriers hindering its development. Photo Illustration: Mike Janson<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>“A lot of other investment is needed in order to really make this work,” said Mariza Cooray, a senior economist at the Indo-Pacific Development Centre at the Lowy Institute, an Australia-based think tank. Complementary infrastructure such as roads and more capacity to capture tourism revenue will require even more borrowing, she said, adding: “They&#39;re really in a kind of debt spiral.”</p><p> The country&#39;s “growing and unsustainable debt burden” is limiting its ability to invest in vital health and education services, said Ben Bland, the Asia-Pacific program director for Chatham House, a UK-based think tank.</p><p> “These are real and pressing short-term pressures, while the returns from the rail project will only be clear in the long term,” Bland said. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818980?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Passengers travel north on the new Laos-China Railway from Vang Vieng, Laos, toward the Chinese border. </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817244?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Lao day laborers who work for a Chinese silk production company wait to be paid for their work.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> But in Laos, Beijing has faced very little resistance. That is in part because Laos, like China, is ruled by an authoritarian communist regime that can act quickly without much scrutiny—and also because its development needs are enormous and China was the only game in town. The country of 7.4 million—with a small workforce and few natural resources—has been of little interest to investors from the West and Japan, which don&#39;t share China&#39;s strategic imperative here.</p><p> It helps China&#39;s case that the train is popular in Laos. Dangerous 12-hour bus rides through mountain roads can now be made in less than four hours by rail, for about the same price. Students and migrant workers can easily visit their families. One couple said they were taking their baby to a hospital in the capital to see a pediatric specialist that their rural province doesn&#39;t have.</p><p> More than 2,000 products are now approved for export via the cargo route, the Laos-China Railway Company said. Fruits such as watermelon and durian, cassava flour, rubber and iron are among the products making their way to China. Mechanical equipment, chemical fertilizers, appliances and solar panels are pouring into Laos.</p><p> When the train launched, Chinese leader Xi Jinping and Lao President Thongloun Sisoulith said the project would bring prosperity to both sides. Just as North America&#39;s first transcontinental railroad created boomtowns across the countryside, Xi promised a “golden route” from which development would spring. Stations were built a few miles outside of towns to make room for urban expansion, with warehouses erected alongside to process cargo. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818982?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> &#39;Chinese investment follows the train,&#39; said He Ming Jia, a senior executive at Yunnan Haicheng Industrial Group.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Chinese firms are snapping up nearby properties to set up farms and factories. About a 30-minute drive from Muang Xai, a town with one of the train&#39;s major stations, the hills are covered with crops bound for the border. Chinese firms have been harvesting on the surrounding land for decades, leasing large plantations to grow bananas, rubber trees, soybeans and cassava—and now they are expanding further.</p><p> At a mulberry farm, women harvest leaves to feed silkworms that are spinning fibers to be woven into fine Chinese fabrics. A new processing plant opened last year for adlay, a grain used in soupy desserts and traditional Chinese medicine.</p><p> Locals have traditionally been subsistence farmers, growing just enough rice and vegetables to feed their families. Saiy Soulivong, 32, said he used to struggle to find shifts on construction sites to earn extra cash. Now he works as a day laborer at a new cluster of warehouses that companies can rent near a train station.</p><p> “We have more options,” he said. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-817254?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Chinese tourists gave alms to Buddhist monks last month in Luang Prabang, one of the major stops on the Laos-China railroad. </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818986?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Workers end their day with dinner at a Chinese restaurant in Boten, Laos.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Laos is no stranger to the influence of foreign powers. Its cities are famous for colonial architecture incorporating French elements. The US scarred its countryside during the Vietnam War, dropping more than two million tons of bombs on communist hide-outs. Unexploded ordnance maimed villagers and slowed development for decades, but Lao society is still largely receptive to American engagement.</p><p> Since cross-border passenger trains launched in April, arrivals from China have surged. On a recent morning in Luang Prabang, a Unesco World Heritage site popular for its ornate temples and natural attractions such as waterfalls, tourists dropped crisp Chinese bank notes as alms for Buddhist monks at a ceremony. Further north, in Boten, the currency is as common as the local Lao kip and signs are printed in both Lao and Mandarin.</p><p> “It&#39;s becoming more like China than like Laos, but it&#39;s good because they build things,” said Noy Keomanychan, a 43-year-old food vendor who commutes from a nearby village to sell grilled meat and squirrel soup to Lao laborers.</p><p> “That&#39;s how it is,” she said, “the Lao people are poor, and the Chinese are rich.”</p><p> Write to Feliz Solomon at <a href="mailto:feliz.solomon@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">feliz.solomon@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Thu, 20 Jul 2023 03:49:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-grand-vision-for-a-vast-rail-network-transforms-a-neighboring-country-17f067cc</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-grand-vision-for-a-vast-rail-network-transforms-a-neighboring-country-17f067cc<author><![CDATA[Feliz Solomon]]></author><category> gfx-contrib</category><category> Heavy Construction</category><category> Railway Construction</category><category> Rail Transport</category><category> Construction</category><category>房地产/建筑</category><category>Land Transport</category><category>运输/物流</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>Economic Zones</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>economic zones</category><category> heavy construction</category><category> railway construction</category><category> rail transport</category><category>建造</category><category>房地产</category><category>land transport</category><category>运输</category><category>后勤</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[U.S. Bans 14 Iraqi Banks in Crackdown on Iran Dollar Trade]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Treasury Department, Federal Reserve Bank of New York bar the lenders from conducting dollar transactions <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001066658"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819908?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> An employee counts bank notes at currency-exchange house in Baghdad.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: murtaja lateef/AFP/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001066658"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/david-s-cloud" itemprop="url" rel="author">David S. Cloud</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated July 19, 2023 6:05 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-sanctions-14-iraqi-banks-in-crackdown-on-iran-dollar-trade-33ef9f35"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> WASHINGTON—The US has barred 14 Iraqi banks from conducting dollar transactions, US officials said, part of a sweeping crackdown on the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/iraqis-fly-to-nearby-countries-to-get-dollars-as-u-s-cracks-down-on-money-laundering-ec366494?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">siphoning of US currency to Iran</a> and other sanctioned Middle East countries.</p><p> The ban, which was imposed Wednesday by the Treasury Department and the Federal Reserve Bank of New York, is likely to provoke new tensions between Baghdad and Washington and could spark more <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/iraq-economy-reels-as-u-s-moves-against-money-flows-to-iran-11674128633?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">economic turmoil for ordinary Iraqis</a> .</p><p> It signals a hardening of sanctions enforcement against Iran only months after the Biden administration <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-launches-quiet-diplomatic-push-with-iran-to-cool-tensions-2f45af3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">appeared intent on lowering tensions</a> with Tehran. The Treasury recently approved a payment of 2.5 billion euros, equivalent to about $2.8 billion, toward unpaid debts by the Iraqi government for Iranian electricity and gas imports, which had been frozen by sanctions.</p><p> Earlier this week, the Pentagon dispatched a warship and jet fighters to the region, saying it was in response to Iranian threats against commercial shipping in the Persian Gulf.</p><p> US officials said they were taking action against the Iraqi banks after uncovering information that they engaged in money laundering and fraudulent transactions, some of which may have involved sanctioned individuals and raised concerns that Iran could benefit.</p><p> US officials said the main goal of the dollar restrictions was to choke off money-laundering in Iraq.</p><p> “We have strong reason to suspect that at least some of these laundered funds could end up going to benefit either designated individuals or individuals who could be designated,” said a senior US official, adding “of course the primary sanctions risk in Iraq relates to Iran.”</p><p> Most of the banks targeted by the US are small institutions, even by Iraqi standards. Several have ties to influential Iraqis, are known for having financial connections with Iran or for heavy involvement in the dollar transactions, according to two Iraqi banking experts.</p><p> Among those on the US list are Al Mustashar Islamic Bank, Erbil Bank, World Islamic Bank and Zain Iraq Islamic Bank. Erbil Bank Chairman Mohammed Saeed Al-Barzanji said in emailed comments that he had not been notified of the dollar ban and said transactions by the bank were carefully checked to prevent fraud. Other banks didn&#39;t return messages seeking comment on the US action. A spokesman for the Central Bank of Iraq also didn&#39;t respond to a request for comment.</p><p> At a Baghdad branch of Al Taif Islamic Bank, another of the targeted banks, several customers in line Wednesday evening were seeking to buy dollars for overseas travel or were receiving dollars in money transfers from abroad. “Things are normal and people as you see receive and send money normally,” said a teller, who declined to give his name.</p><p> Iran has long used neighboring Iraq as a source of hard currency denied to it by US sanctions, drawing on its strong links to many Iraqi politicians and the easy availability of dollars in Iraq&#39;s loosely regulated currency markets.</p><p> The dollar has functioned as a virtual second official currency in Iraq since greenbacks flooded into the country after the 2003 US invasion. Two decades later, Iraq still keeps its foreign currency reserves at the New York Fed, depositing the proceeds from its sales of oil in official accounts there.</p><p> Iraqi banks and currency-exchange houses figured out how to make huge profits from the dollar, using fraudulent import transactions and other schemes, according to current and former US and Iraqi officials. The dollars bought from the central bank at a fixed rate could be resold at the often sharply higher market rate.</p><p> Blocking access to dollars is a slow death sentence for many Iraqi banks, which have few depositors and make minimal commercial loans, relying on dollar transactions for most of their profits, US officials and Iraqi bankers say. Over two decades, the Iraqi dollar trade has become a source of its endemic corruption, as bankers formed alliances with Iraq&#39;s powerful militias and politicians to secure access to US currency.</p><p> When the Treasury and the Central Bank of Iraq cut off four other banks from access to dollars and imposed tighter controls on wire transfers in November last year, the Iraqi dinar plunged against the dollar and prices of imported goods shot up, resulting in a three-month crisis for Iraqi Prime Minister Mohammed al-Sudani. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819910?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The depreciation of the Iraqi dinar against the dollar led to protesting in Iraq.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: ahmad al-rubaye/AFP/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The measures triggered daily dollar transfers through Iraqi commercial banks, which sometimes totaled over $250 million a day, to fall by 80% or more, as lenders struggled to comply with requirements to provide detailed information about where the money was going.</p><p> The tighter scrutiny of dollar transactions since last year helped the Fed identify the 14 banks that were conducting suspicious transactions, the officials said.</p><p> Several of the banks had stopped conducting wire transfers in recent months, another US official said, apparently unable to supply sufficient information for the Fed to approve the transaction.</p><p> Some employed new schemes for moving dollars illicitly, including shifting transactions to different banks in hopes of escaping Fed scrutiny, the senior official said. Others tried using scores of cash cards loaded with dinars in Iraq and then transported to nearby countries where the funds could be withdrawn in dollars, he added.</p><p> To escape scrutiny, some banks also expanded their use of Western money-transfer firms and informal Middle East networks for moving cash, known as hawalla, he said.</p><p> The officials played down the impact of the latest US move on the Iraqi economy, citing internal statistics that showed the 14 banks combined held only 1.29% of Iraq&#39;s total banking assets. Much of Iraq&#39;s legitimate banking activity is conducted by state-owned banks and the country has another 46 commercial banks unaffected by the dollar ban, they added.</p><p> One effect of the move could be to drive back up the unofficial Iraqi exchange rate, which has fallen to as low as 1,470 dinars to the dollar since reaching over 1,620 Iraqi dinars to the dollar earlier this year. US officials said they expected any increase to be temporary.</p><p> Since the Treasury and the New York Fed began scrutinizing dollar activity more aggressively last fall, the number of fraudulent transactions being funneled through Iraq&#39;s foreign-exchange system has been reduced, the officials said, which will lessen the economic impact of banning additional banks.</p><p> “Because there&#39;s more real trade occurring, versus essentially trade-based money laundering, we expect a much less meaningful drop in activity,” said the senior official.</p><p> Sudani has said that the greater scrutiny of dollar flows by US and Iraqi authorities since last fall caused economic upheaval. But the Iraqi premier has acknowledged the weakness of Iraq&#39;s banks and credited the stricter limits on dollar transactions with halting fraudulent transactions.</p><p> “Unfortunately we do not have a banking system, whether government or private one, and this is a real problem,” Sudani said in remarks at the Iraq Forum, a policy conference in Baghdad put on by the Middle East Research Institute, in May. “It was a money laundering process, smuggling of currency and a fake trade with fake documents.”</p><p> US officials have pressed Iraq for years to strengthen its banking controls. In 2015, the Federal Reserve and the Treasury Department briefly shut off the flow of dollars to Iraq&#39;s central bank over concerns that the currency was ending up at Iranian banks and possibly being funneled to Islamic State militants, officials said at the time.</p><p> But successive US administrations feared that cutting off Baghdad&#39;s access to dollars completely would plunge the country into economic turmoil, jeopardizing other goals, such as preventing the re-emergence of Islamic State and driving Baghdad away from Tehran. But US officials say they hope Baghdad will begin to take more steps against money laundering and fraud in its banking system.</p><p> “What we&#39;re looking for is for Iraq to take more proactive action, because what we don&#39;t want is just to have to constantly play whack-a-mole,” said the senior official.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Ghassan Adnan in Baghdad contributed to this article.</p><p> Write to David S. Cloud at <a href="mailto:david.cloud@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">david.cloud@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 19 Jul 2023 22:05:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-sanctions-14-iraqi-banks-in-crackdown-on-iran-dollar-trade-33ef9f35</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-sanctions-14-iraqi-banks-in-crackdown-on-iran-dollar-trade-33ef9f35<author><![CDATA[David S. Cloud]]></author><category> iran</category><category>华尔街日报</category><category>专有的</category><category>Banking/Credit</category><category>金融服务</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>金融犯罪</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>Iran</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>金融犯罪</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>banking</category><category>信用</category><category>financial services </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[China Tries to Reassure U.S. Amid Speculation Around Missing Foreign Minister]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Qin Gang, former ambassador in Washington, hasn&#39;t been seen in public for more than three weeks <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001066232"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=9F7AF9B6-88BC-4AB6-B4C8-E0CF0C68E116&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fchina-tries-to-reassure-u-s-amid-speculation-around-missing-foreign-minister-82697971&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> The prolonged disappearance of China&#39;s foreign minister, Qin Gang, has led to intense speculation over his whereabouts. Qin&#39;s absence highlights the lack of transparency in the governance of the world&#39;s second-largest economy. Photo: Noel Celis/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001066232"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/lingling-wei" itemprop="url" rel="author">Lingling Wei</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated July 19, 2023 5:18 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-tries-to-reassure-u-s-amid-speculation-around-missing-foreign-minister-82697971"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Intrigue is intensifying around the whereabouts of Chinese leader Xi Jinping&#39;s handpicked foreign minister, with Beijing assuring Washington the recent thaw in high-level contacts will continue despite the diplomat&#39;s absence from public view.</p><p> Chinese Foreign Minister Qin Gang, until recently Beijing&#39;s top envoy to Washington, hasn&#39;t been seen in public for more than three weeks, skipping major diplomatic engagements and fueling speculation both inside and outside China about what happened to him. The uncertainty comes at a fragile moment when China and the US have been trying to restart high-level exchanges between the two world powers.</p><p> Qin&#39;s absence was particularly notable at an international gathering of foreign ministers last week in Indonesia, where he was slated to meet with US Secretary of State Antony Blinken. Qin&#39;s place was taken by Wang Yi, a member of the Communist Party&#39;s elite Politburo and China&#39;s top foreign-affairs official.</p><p> Wang told Blinken that the absence of the 57-year-old Qin was for “health reasons,” repeating a public explanation given by China&#39;s Foreign Ministry, people familiar with the matter said. Wang told his US counterpart that Beijing will maintain open channels of communication with Washington.</p><p> Blinken invited Qin to visit the US during the top American diplomat&#39;s <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/after-months-of-cold-shoulder-china-welcomes-blinken-to-beijing-84b51627?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">trip to Beijing last month</a> —an offer Qin had accepted as part of continuing efforts by both sides to restore lines of communication disrupted by a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinese-spy-balloon-over-the-u-s-what-to-know-11675385792?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">suspected Chinese balloon</a> early this year.</p><p> No date had been announced for that meeting, though Chinese officials had expected it to occur in the lead-up to a potential trip by Xi to an annual summit of Asia-Pacific leaders in San Francisco in November.</p><p> Asked about Qin&#39;s absence, State Department spokesman Matthew Miller said Monday that Blinken “expressed his best wishes to see him soon” during his meeting with Wang.</p><p> China&#39;s Foreign Ministry sent a one-line statement in reply to a request for comment. “China&#39;s diplomatic activities are steadily advancing,” it said.</p><p> China&#39;s recently installed ambassador in Washington sidestepped questions about Qin during an appearance Wednesday at a forum in Aspen, Colo. Asked about whether Henry Kissinger,</p> who is on a visit to Beijing, would meet with Qin, Ambassador Xie Feng said, “Let&#39;s wait and see.” When pressed again about Qin, Xie said the Foreign Ministry had already briefed the media. “Thank you for your care,” he said.<p></p><p> The foreign minister was last seen on June 25, when Qin met counterparts from Vietnam and Sri Lanka, as well as Russian Deputy Foreign Minister Rudenko Andrey Yurevich, shortly after a botched armed rebellion in Russia. Qin was set to meet with the European Union&#39;s foreign-policy head Josep Borell in Beijing on July 10, but Beijing canceled the visit five days earlier without explanation.</p><p> Qin didn&#39;t meet with Treasury Secretary Janet Yellen during her visit to Beijing in early July. He has also been absent from meetings with US climate envoy John Kerry, who was set to wrap up a four-day visit to China on Wednesday.</p><p> Qin&#39;s vanishing from the public stage has spurred new questions about the governance of the world&#39;s second-largest economy at a time when the Communist Party <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-locks-information-on-the-country-inside-a-black-box-9c039928?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">has doubled down</a> on its penchant for secrecy, making it evermore difficult to access information about what is happening inside China. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="488" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819748?width=700&amp;height=488" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> US Secretary of State Antony Blinken with Chinese Foreign Minister Qin Gang in Beijing on June 18.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Leah Millis/Press Pool</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Considered a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-promotes-u-s-ambassador-to-foreign-minister-11672409545?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">trusted aide to Xi</a> , Qin climbed the ranks from China&#39;s ambassador to the US to Beijing&#39;s foreign minister in less than two years—an unusually fast promotion in a system that traditionally has valued experience in addition to political connections.</p><p> Xi promoted Qin to be his foreign minister late last year as the top leader embarked on his <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-xi-claims-third-term-as-communist-party-leader-11666499842?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">norm-busting third term</a> in power. The Chinese leader in particular valued Qin&#39;s ability to “present China&#39;s position well” during his time serving as his top envoy to Washington, one of the people familiar with the matter said.</p><p> Qin&#39;s close association with the top leader has made his absence all the more intriguing. An information void has fed furious speculation on social media, including around the possibility of an extramarital affair.</p><p> The foreign ministry first addressed Qin&#39;s disappearance on July 11, when it disclosed at a regular press briefing that he wouldn&#39;t attend last week&#39;s international gathering of foreign ministers in Jakarta because of “health reasons,” without giving any details. Since then, spokespeople at the foreign ministry have sidestepped questions about Qin, with mentions of the foreign minister recently omitted from the transcripts of daily press briefings.</p><p> In the opaque Chinese system, issues related to health are commonly given as the reason for a senior official&#39;s absence.党内人士表示，这种解释通常是真实的，尽管有时可以掩盖政治问题。 When Wang Lijun, the former head of police in the inland megacity of Chongqing, went missing in February 2012, the city government said he was taking “ <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/BL-CJB-15144?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">vacation-style treatment</a> ” for stress and overwork. In reality, he <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702303459004577362360212353368?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">had fled to the US consulate</a> in the nearby city of Chengdu to seek asylum.</p><p> Ryan Hass, a former adviser on China and Asia at the National Security Council under the Obama administration, said Qin&#39;s disappearance conjured up “the image of a duck swimming in relation to China&#39;s bureaucratic politics—serene above the water and violent kicking below it.”</p><p> Still, Hass, now director of the China Center at the Brookings Institution think tank in Washington, said Qin&#39;s absence “will not dramatically alter the tenor or substance of US-China diplomatic exchanges.” The role of China&#39;s foreign minister is to articulate and implement China&#39;s policies abroad, but he isn&#39;t the sole architect of those policies, he said.</p><p> In recent days, Wang, the top foreign-affairs official, has stepped in for the foreign minister on many occasions.周一，当中国领导人在北京会见菲律宾前总统罗德里戈·杜特尔特时，王毅和外交部副部长与习近平会面。 A day later, Wang met with Kerry.</p><p> A diplomatic priority for Beijing this year is to pave the way for Xi to attend the Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation summit in San Francisco—and possibly meet one-on-one there with President Biden. That priority, along with China&#39;s weakening economy, gives China&#39;s leadership incentives to re-engage with the US</p><p> <em>—Charles Hutzler and Wenxin Fan contributed to this article.</em></p><p> Write to Lingling Wei at <a href="mailto:Lingling.Wei@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Lingling.Wei@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 19 Jul 2023 21:18:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-tries-to-reassure-us-amid-speculation-around-missing-foreign-minister-82697971</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-tries-to-reassure-us-amid-speculation-around-missing-foreign-minister-82697971<author><![CDATA[Lingling Wei]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Qin Gang</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>国内政治</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Tech Stocks, Meme Stocks, Crypto: Investors Are Feeling Bold Again]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The market looks a lot like 2021—right before stocks entered a deep slump <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001060252"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          header
"><img width="600" height="944" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/bb20594b-6619-40f6-aef7-62458b1388a4-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001060252"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/eric-wallerstein" itemprop="url" rel="author">Eric Wallerstein</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated July 19, 2023 4:41 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tech-stocks-meme-stocks-crypto-investors-are-feeling-bold-again-f158812b"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> For many investors, it is like 2022 never happened.</p><p> Tech stocks are rising manically, spilling into meme stocks. The cryptoverse is enjoying a resurgence. Bullishness is hitting a fever pitch in the options market. In short, risk-on investments are the most popular they have been since late 2021—right before stocks entered the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/stock-market-today-dow-jones-06-08-2023/card/s-p-500-says-goodbye-to-its-longest-bear-market-since-the-1940s-vu6HsVabVKb5dcbg6qgI?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">longest bear market in decades</a> .</p><h3> Speculative stocks are soaring</h3><p> Shades of meme-stock mania are cropping up. The MEME ETF—tied to the Solactive Roundhill Meme Stock Index—has risen 67% this year to its highest level since May 2022.</p><p> Its top holdings as of Monday included bitcoin miner <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/RIOT" class="company-name">Riot Platforms</a> (up 458% this year), artificial-intelligence lending platform <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/UPST" class="company-name">Upstart Holdings</a> (up 342%), <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/COIN" class="company-name">Coinbase Global</a> (up 211%), electric-car maker Rivian Automotive (up 35%), and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/CVNA" class="company-name">Carvana</a> (up 1,077%). The fervor has driven <a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/stock-market-today-dow-jones-07-03-2023/card/one-big-bet-traders-love-rivian-and-other-electric-car-makers-qQAn9OI9Kf8ih19Cu75Y?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">record-high options trading</a> tied to many of those companies&#39; shares.</p><p> And <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bitcoin-coinbase-are-soaring-despite-obstacles-facing-spot-bitcoin-etfs-d028ddab?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">against all odds</a> , bitcoin has climbed 81% in 2023. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819928?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><h3> Individual investors are amped</h3><p> Retail traders <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/this-bull-market-is-just-getting-started-traders-bet-bd9fd930?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">are all-in</a> . Bullish sentiment—represented as the expectation that stocks will rise in the next six months—this month hit its highest level since 2021, according to surveys by the American Association of Individual Investors.</p><p> The bull-bear spread, the difference between investors who see the stock market trotting higher versus those expecting a rout, has been positive for six consecutive weeks. That is the longest stretch since November 2021.</p><p> Americans are also growing more confident about the economy as a whole. Consumer sentiment, measured by the University of Michigan&#39;s survey, jumped to 72.6 in July from 64.4 the prior month. That is the highest reading since September 2021 and the biggest increase since 2005. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="700" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818739?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Since the Federal Reserve rescued the banking system in March, investors have had <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/investor-anxiety-hits-a-fever-pitch-after-silicon-valley-bank-collapse-3cbf94b7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">less to worry about</a> , according to David Wagner, a portfolio manager at Aptus Capital Advisors. “The only thing that can stop this rally is if a big time risk is put back on the table,” he said.</p><h3> Fear has faded</h3><p> Rather than scoop up options that would protect portfolios&#39; gains if stocks fell, investors are reaching for bets that would pay out if the rally continued. The put-call ratio—a measure of fear in the options market—has fallen to its lowest levels since January 2022, according to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/CBOE" class="company-name">Cboe Global Markets</a> data.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>Do you think the stock-market rally can be sustained?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> The Cboe Volatility Index, or the VIX, is trading below 14. The index is commonly referred to as Wall Street&#39;s fear gauge as it measures prices of options used to protect against market declines. Anything below 20 is associated with <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-stock-market-isnt-as-calm-as-it-seems-3713180c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">little demand for insurance</a> .</p><p> One reason why investors look complacent to many in the market is that stocks are quietly marching higher. The S&amp;P 500&#39;s daily swings haven&#39;t been this small since late 2021, according to a Cboe measure. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="740" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820246?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><h3> How it could unravel</h3><p> Market contrarians say the perfect storm is brewing <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/five-ways-the-bull-market-makes-investors-nervous-2f0bf74c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">for a crash</a> .</p><p> Retail investors were similarly euphoric in late 2021. They showed few signs of unnerve: The put-call ratio was low, as was the VIX. But by early January 2022, all three major stock indexes had peaked, and the S&amp;P 500 went on to lose 19% that year. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=A76A224A-34F0-4334-B5D2-D416C227FC71&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Ftech-stocks-meme-stocks-crypto-investors-are-feeling-bold-again-f158812b&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Crypto imploded in 2022, as investors lost faith in digital assets and the industry was plagued with crisis. But unlike other collapses, it has largely avoided rippling into other markets. WSJ explains how crypto became so interconnected. Illustration: Mallory Brangan<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>“The FOMO [fear of missing out] becomes so great that retail investors come clamoring in at the end, the last hurrah, just in time for the market bottom to fall out,” said</p> Amanda Agati, chief investment officer of PNC Asset Management Group.<p></p><p> It isn&#39;t just the exuberance that is giving some cause for concern. Higher borrowing costs threaten to slow down the economy, choking off <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fed-rate-increases-are-squeezing-consumer-finance-companies-11670712247?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">credit for businesses</a> and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/where-is-the-u-s-economy-headed-follow-the-money-c79a6b1c?page=1&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">making it harder</a> for companies and households to get loans. Over the past year or so, rates on auto loans and mortgages have jumped around 3 percentage points. Interest on credit cards is up to 22% from 16%, Federal Reserve data show. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="650" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818745?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> While inflation has eased, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/consumer-price-index-report-june-inflation-ede7f4b1?page=1&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">hitting 3% in June</a> , it is still above the Fed&#39;s target rate of 2%. And Fed officials are likely concerned about Americans getting used to elevated inflation.</p><p> “If we get stagflation, rates will have to continue rising,” said Jason Bloom, head of fixed income and alternatives ETF strategy for Invesco. “That&#39;s not a great recipe for investors.”</p><p> Write to Eric Wallerstein at <a href="mailto:eric.wallerstein@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">eric.wallerstein@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/e0815ea6-ecc0-4136-bdae-5d2167589c29.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 19 Jul 2023 20:41:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/tech-stocks-meme-stocks-crypto-investors-are-feeling-bold-again-f158812b</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/tech-stocks-meme-stocks-crypto-investors-are-feeling-bold-again-f158812b<author><![CDATA[Eric Wallerstein]]></author><category>华尔街日报财经</category><category>wsjfinance-markets</category><category> gfx-contrib</category><category> Credit Types/Services</category><category> Consumer Lending</category><category> Financial Investment Services</category><category> Securities/Commodity Exchange Activities</category><category> Banking/Credit</category><category>金融服务</category><category>Financial Technology</category><category> Investing/Securities</category><category>技术</category><category>Virtual Currencies/Cryptocurrencies</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>IWE过滤器</category><category>Routine Market/Financial News</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Jason Bloom</category><category> Amanda Agati</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>伊威过滤器</category><category>routine market</category><category> financial news</category><category> credit types</category><category>服务</category><category>consumer lending</category><category> financial investment services</category><category> securities</category><category> commodity exchange activities</category><category> banking</category><category>信用</category><category>financial services</category><category> financial technology</category><category> investing</category><category>技术</category><category>virtual currencies</category><category> cryptocurrencies </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Ex-Venezuelan Spy Chief Extradited to U.S. on Drug Charges After Long Manhunt]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Hugo &#39;The Chicken&#39; Carvajal could provide US prosecutors with evidence of crimes by top Venezuelan officials <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001067440"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819862?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Hugo Carvajal, pictured in 2019, was extradited Wednesday to the US from Spain.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: POOL/REUTERS </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001067440"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/kejal-vyas" itemprop="url" rel="author">Kejal Vyas</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/juan-forero" itemprop="url" rel="author">Juan Forero</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 19, 2023 2:13 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ex-venezuelan-spy-chief-extradited-to-u-s-on-drug-charges-after-long-manhunt-9f17954d"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> BOGOTÁ, Colombia— Hugo Carvajal, a former Venezuelan spy chief long wanted by the US on charges that he <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/venezuelan-officials-suspected-of-turning-country-into-global-cocaine-hub-1431977784?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">collaborated with narco-terrorists to traffic cocaine</a> , was extradited Wednesday to the US from Spain, according to the Justice Department.</p><p> Carvajal, a confidant of President Hugo Chávez until his death in 2013, could provide US prosecutors with information on figures in Venezuela&#39;s authoritarian regime involved in cocaine-smuggling, corruption and money laundering, people familiar with his case say.</p><p> Carvajal, 63 years old, known as  “El Pollo,” or “The Chicken,” because of his long neck, has repeatedly denied the US&#39;s allegations, calling them politically motivated. Carvajal is expected to appear before a magistrate court at the Southern District of New York on Thursday and plead not guilty, his defense lawyer Zachary Margulis-Ohnuma said.</p><p> “Testifying against others—that&#39;s where the real value is,”  said a person who had been close to Carvajal and had worked with US antidrug agents. “He knows about people who are in the structure,” he said, explaining that Carvajal would know about narco-trafficking and kleptocracy in high Venezuelan government circles.</p><p> Since 2019, Carvajal had been in Madrid <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ex-venezuela-military-spy-chief-arrested-11555100543?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">fighting extradition proceedings</a> after <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/venezuelan-official-breaks-with-maduro-11550791292?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">breaking from Chávez&#39;s successor</a> , President Nicolás Maduro, and fleeing from Venezuela. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819863?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Spanish police arrested Hugo Carvajal in this building in Madrid.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Manu Fernandez/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Carvajal&#39;s long tenure as the head of the South American nation&#39;s military counterintelligence offers American investigators insights into the inner workings of the Venezuelan regime and its alleged ties to Colombian narcotics traffickers, Marxist guerrillas, arms dealers and international money-laundering operations, said people who have worked on US cases against Venezuelan officials.</p><p> “When you look at what he can provide on intelligence outside the scope of the judicial context, it&#39;s going to be very rich in content,” said Wesley Tabor, a former US Drug Enforcement Administration attaché in Venezuela who had investigated Carvajal.</p><p> “The information could lead to disruptions and dismantlement of various criminal organizations worldwide,” said Tabor, who now heads the Celebrity Consulting Group in Florida.</p><p> Carvajal&#39;s extradition comes as the US has been pressuring Maduro to resume negotiations with the opposition to stage free and fair presidential elections next year. But Maduro, who has angrily bristled at Washington&#39;s sanctions and the indictments against top regime officials, has instead <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/venezuela-bans-a-top-opposition-figure-from-public-office-11373568?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">disqualified leading opposition candidates</a> from running in the race and barred European elections observers.</p><p> In 2020, US prosecutors in New York&#39;s Southern District <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-indicts-venezuelan-president-nicolas-maduro-on-allegations-of-drug-trafficking-11585236443?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">charged Maduro</a> , Carvajal and another senior Venezuelan official, Diosdado Cabello,</p> on charges of working with Colombian drug-trafficking groups to “flood” the US with cocaine, using the drug “as a weapon against America.”<p></p><p> The Maduro administration has denied the charges, calling them “a collection of dirty, false accusations.”</p><p> Venezuela has angrily denounced <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/deal-maker-for-venezuelas-maduro-regime-extradited-to-u-s-11634432668?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the 2021 extradition</a> of Alex Saab, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/key-financier-of-venezuelas-maduro-regime-arrested-11592078537?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a key Maduro financier</a> who the US accuses of money laundering and helping the Venezuelan government evade US economic sanctions.</p><p> Saab has also denied the charges. But former Venezuelan prosecutors and people familiar with his case say he, like Carvajal, holds confidential information that could aid US intelligence and antinarcotics agents investigating the Maduro regime&#39;s murky financial deals with other US adversaries such as Iran and Russia, which have helped Caracas outlast American sanctions.</p><p> US investigators say they have been painstakingly piecing together information about the regime&#39;s alleged ties to drug trafficking.</p><p> Last month, one of Carvajal&#39;s co-defendants, Cliver Alcalá, a retired Venezuelan army general, told a New York court that he provided protection and weapons, including grenade launchers, to the now-defunct rebel group, the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, or FARC. Alcala, who pleaded guilty to US charges of collaborating with the FARC, had turned into a critic of Maduro and surrendered to US law enforcement.</p><p> Carvajal had proven more elusive, leading American officials on a long international manhunt. In 2011, US attorneys in New York charged him with conspiracy to smuggle 5.6 tons of cocaine to the US via Mexico in 2006.</p><p> In 2014, Carvajal was detained on a US warrant in the Dutch Caribbean island of Aruba, where the Maduro government was preparing to name him as Venezuela&#39;s envoy. Venezuela&#39;s government pressured Aruba to release him, and he received a hero&#39;s welcome orchestrated by Maduro upon his return to Venezuela.</p><p> Carvajal split from the government in 2019 after publicly denouncing Maduro for alleged human rights violations during political protests.</p><p> After fleeing to Spain, Carvajal was arrested again on the US charges in April 2019. Months later, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/spain-releases-former-venezuelan-spy-chief-wanted-by-u-s-on-drug-charges-11568653834?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">he was released by a Spanish court</a> as his extradition process was under way and went into hiding.</p><p> Write to Kejal Vyas at <a href="mailto:kejal.vyas@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">kejal.vyas@wsj.com</a> and Juan Forero at <a href="mailto:juan.forero@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">juan.forero@wsj.com</a></p><p id="correction" class="correction"><strong>更正和放大</strong><br>Venezuela&#39;s former spy chief Hugo Carvajal is 63 years old. An earlier version of this article incorrectly said he is 61. (Corrected on July 19)</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 19 Jul 2023 18:13:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ex-venezuelan-spy-chief-extradited-to-us-on-drug-charges-after-long-manhunt-9f17954d</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ex-venezuelan-spy-chief-extradited-to-us-on-drug-charges-after-long-manhunt-9f17954d<author><![CDATA[Kejal VyasJuan Forero]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>Corruption</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>Drug Trafficking/Dealing</category><category> Money Laundering</category><category>金融犯罪</category><category>Espionage</category><category> Trafficking/Smuggling</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Hugo Carvajal</category><category> Hugo Chávez</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>corruption</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>drug trafficking</category><category> dealing</category><category> money laundering</category><category>金融犯罪</category><category>espionage</category><category> trafficking</category><category> smuggling</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Kerry’s China Trip Restores Talks on Climate Change But Falls Short on Agreement]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Visit by the US climate envoy tests Beijing&#39;s willingness to find common ground <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001067204"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=AEFDD20E-B8EC-4F14-B1AA-8439E0D73B67&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fkerrys-china-trip-restores-talks-on-climate-change-but-falls-short-on-agreement-f89be8e2&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Special Presidential Envoy for Climate John Kerry met with Chinese Premier Li Qiang in a visit aimed to try to revive stalled cooperation on climate change. Photo: Florence Lo/Reuters<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001067204"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sha-hua" itemprop="url" rel="author">Sha Hua</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 19, 2023 1:43 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/kerrys-china-trip-restores-talks-on-climate-change-but-falls-short-on-agreement-f89be8e2"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> John Kerry, the US special envoy on climate, concluded talks in China that pushed forward the two powers&#39; tentative effort to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-china-start-talking-again-with-global-economic-order-at-stake-9b49a10b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">reset fraught ties</a> and tested Beijing&#39;s willingness to find common ground on <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-sets-heat-record-as-john-kerry-arrives-to-discuss-climate-6a35c686?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">fighting climate change</a> .</p><p> Kerry saw a parade of high-level Chinese officials and spent long hours in closed-door meetings with his counterpart during his three days in Beijing. Both sides came away citing a readiness for future discussions on climate change after nearly a year of little contact due to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/restricting-chip-sales-to-china-could-backfire-on-u-s-industry-group-says-dbb7b8df?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Beijing&#39;s anger</a> with Washington <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/taiwans-vice-president-plans-stop-in-the-u-s-at-a-delicate-moment-886e484b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">over Taiwan</a> , technology and other issues.</p><p> “We came here to unstick what had been stuck,” Kerry told reporters Wednesday. “And indeed, we did succeed.”</p><p> While both sides agreed to future collaboration, Kerry said, they couldn&#39;t finalize all the details. Nor did he get an audience with Chinese leader Xi Jinping, who instead attended a conference on environmental protection and sent a signal on Beijing&#39;s limits for engagement.</p><p> In remarks to that gathering, Xi reiterated <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-ambitious-climate-goals-collide-with-reality-imperiling-global-efforts-11635346919?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">China&#39;s goals</a> to see its climate-warming emissions peak before 2030 and become carbon neutral before 2060. But he underscored that his government would proceed on its own timetable despite pressure from the Biden administration to accelerate the time frame.</p><p> “The pathway, pace and the vigor with which to achieve these goals should and must be determined by ourselves, and free from outside interference,” Xi said, according to state media reports. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819853?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> China&#39;s top foreign-policy official, Wang Yi, said that the climate issue couldn&#39;t be detached from the overall state of bilateral relations with the US</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: FLORENCE LO/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The Biden administration has marked out climate, along with the global economy and public health, as areas ripe for cooperation with Beijing to offset the US and China&#39;s bare-knuckled rivalry <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-looks-to-restrict-chinas-access-to-cloud-computing-to-protect-advanced-technology-f771613?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">over technology</a> and global primacy.</p><p> In getting Beijing&#39;s assent to talk more, Kerry met <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/after-months-of-cold-shoulder-china-welcomes-blinken-to-beijing-84b51627?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the low bar</a> set by Secretary of State <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/xi-jinping-to-meet-blinken-monday-as-u-s-china-resume-high-level-engagement-c898f541?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Antony Blinken</a> and Treasury Secretary <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/yellen-trip-aids-fragile-effort-by-u-s-china-to-keep-talking-9b78ea55?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Janet Yellen</a> on their <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/yellen-trip-aids-fragile-effort-by-u-s-china-to-keep-talking-9b78ea55?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">recent trips to Beijing</a> as the two governments resume high-level contacts.</p><p> Kerry said he and his Chinese interlocutors were already discussing the next two sets of meetings ahead of the upcoming climate summit in Dubai at the end of the year. Points of further discussion, he said, include new emission goals for 2035 and ways to reduce emissions of methane and other non-carbon dioxide emissions. China&#39;s use of coal, Kerry said, remains a contentious issue.</p><p> For this visit, the concrete results are less important than the fact there was sustained, constructive communication, said Michael Davidson, assistant professor at the School of Global Policy and Strategy at the University of California, San Diego.</p><p> “It&#39;s a stepping stone to more robust engagement on climate,” Davidson said. Further commitments, he said, could be announced in Dubai or at a potential meeting between Xi and President Biden late this year.</p><p> As the world&#39;s two largest greenhouse-gas emitters, Kerry said, the US and China recognize the urgency of tackling climate change as swaths of the US, Europe and China <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/extreme-heat-waves-across-the-world-photos-7cc1544d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">experience record heat waves</a> in recent days.</p><p> In their meeting Tuesday, Chinese Premier</p> Li Qiang, the country&#39;s No. 2-ranked leader, said that the two countries should “act promptly to form a joint force to deal with climate change.”<p></p><p> Republicans and other critics of the Biden administration have been critical of the recent high-level outreach as engaging in empty talk without advancing US interests.</p><p> When Kerry appeared before the House Foreign Affairs Committee last week, its chairman, Rep. Michael McCaul (R., Texas), pointed to China&#39;s human-rights abuses and its unwillingness to make bigger cuts in carbon-dioxide emissions.</p><p> McCaul also faulted China for keeping its developing country status, as designated by the United Nations, and for insisting that it not be held to the same standards as developed countries, despite being the world&#39;s second largest economy and largest greenhouse gas emitter.</p><p> Since taking up the envoy post, Kerry has tried to keep climate issues separate from wider diplomatic disputes between the two countries. He told Chinese officials that he would convey Beijing&#39;s concerns to Washington but wanted to steer clear of contentious issues, including concerns over forced labor in the clean-energy supply chain or rising tensions in the Taiwan Strait.</p><p> He told reporters that he hopes “nothing will get in the way of us dealing with the climate crisis.”</p><p> In contrast, Chinese officials have seen Kerry as a way to reach Biden and leverage administration <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/biden-administration-targets-power-plant-emissions-in-new-climate-initiative-cb635552?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">interest in climate change</a> to influence US policy.</p><p> China&#39;s top foreign-policy official, Wang Yi, told Kerry during their meeting Tuesday that the climate issue couldn&#39;t be detached from the overall state of bilateral relations.</p><p> Wang also called Kerry “an old friend”—a reference to their overlapping past tenures as their countries&#39; foreign ministers.</p><p> Kerry&#39;s overall smooth interactions with Chinese interlocutors during his trip will only confirm his critics&#39; views that he is soft on China, said Ilaria Mazzocco, a senior fellow at the Center for Strategic and International Studies, a Washington, DC, think tank.</p><p> Competition over clean-energy technology, such as solar panels and batteries, as well as the critical minerals necessary to produce them, might further narrow the space for cooperation, said Mazzocco.</p><p> “This may make it even harder to delink climate from other issues in the relationship,” she said.</p><p> Cooperating on climate change had been a rare bright spot in the testy relationship between the countries. Kerry&#39;s counterpart Xie Zhenhua told Chinese reporters Monday that he and Kerry had spoken to one another 53 times since their respective appointments in early 2021.</p><p> Those frequent interactions ground to a halt after then-House Speaker <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/nancy-pelosi">Nancy Pelosi</a> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/nancy-pelosi-taiwan-visit-china-us-tensions" target="_blank" class="icon none">visited Taiwan</a> last year over Beijing&#39;s vehement objections. The talks resumed again three months later on the sidelines of a global climate gathering in Egypt but were derailed again earlier this year, when Xie suffered a stroke and a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinese-balloon-used-american-tech-to-spy-on-americans-2e3f5039?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">suspected Chinese spy balloon</a> drifted across the US</p><p> Write to Sha Hua at <a href="mailto:sha.hua@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">sha.hua@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 19 Jul 2023 17:43:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/kerrys-china-trip-restores-talks-on-climate-change-but-falls-short-on-agreement-f89be8e2</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/kerrys-china-trip-restores-talks-on-climate-change-but-falls-short-on-agreement-f89be8e2<author><![CDATA[Sha Hua]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>气候变化</category><category>国际关系</category><category>自然环境</category><category>全球/世界问题</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>约翰·克里</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>气候变化</category><category>国际关系</category><category>自然环境</category><category>全球的</category><category>世界问题</category><category>政治</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Travis King, U.S. Soldier Held in North Korea, Had Been Detained in South Korea]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> The American&#39;s &#39;willful&#39; entry to the North instead of facing disciplinary actions creates fresh challenge for Washington and Pyongyang <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001066508"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=D69C17D9-A239-4491-A945-60AAB8A04205&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Ftravis-king-u-s-soldier-held-in-north-korea-had-been-detained-in-south-korea-4cded529&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> The White House press secretary said the US was working with North Korean authorities after an American soldier, identified as Army Private First Class Travis King, crossed over the military demarcation line while on a tour of the Joint Security Area on Tuesday.照片：安东尼·华莱士/法新社/盖蒂图片社<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001066508"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dasl-yoon" itemprop="url" rel="author">Dasl Yoon</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/timothy-w-martin" itemprop="url" rel="author">Timothy W. Martin</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 19, 2023 11:19 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/travis-king-u-s-soldier-held-in-north-korea-had-been-detained-in-south-korea-4cded529"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> SEOUL—The US soldier <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-us-national-custody-b53b4449?mod=hp_featst_pos4&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">being held in North Korea</a> had faced assault allegations in South Korea last year and spent nearly seven weeks in a detention facility, according to US officials, <strong>&nbsp;</strong> as new details emerged about the legal issues faced by an American who crossed the Korean border.</p><p> The fate of the soldier, identified as Army Private 2nd Class Travis King, has handed Washington a fresh challenge in its relations with Pyongyang as <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-nuclear-capable-boomer-sub-visits-south-korea-for-first-time-in-decades-dc4a8187?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">tensions have been rising</a> on the Korean Peninsula.</p><p> King, 23, remained in North Korean custody on Wednesday after crossing the border without authorization the previous day while on <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-officer-on-a-pink-phone-dials-down-north-korea-tensions-11558287392?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a tour of the Joint Security Area</a> , which is within the Demilitarized Zone separating the two Koreas. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="1068" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/867c108b-9cd5-4f9d-b318-b15cf01feec4-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Adm. John Aquilino, the head of US Indo-Pacific Command, said on Tuesday that the military was investigating the situation and that, as far as he knew, the US hadn&#39;t been in contact with North Korea regarding the soldier. North Korea hasn&#39;t commented on King.</p><p>根据金的服役记录，他是一名骑兵侦察兵，自 2021 年 1 月起一直在陆军服役，但没有服役。 He was held at a detention facility in South Korea for 47 days, and spent about a week <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-end-of-small-town-america-in-the-heart-of-seoul-11567503006?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">at Camp Humphreys</a> —a large US Army base in South Korea—before being escorted by military officers to Incheon International Airport, US officials said. On Monday, he had been set to board a flight to Texas, where he would face disciplinary actions and a potential discharge, the officials said.</p><p> King was involved in two alleged assaults, according to a representative at a Seoul court that sentenced him. In September, he allegedly assaulted a South Korean citizen, outside of a nightclub in Hongdae, a popular shopping and nightlife district in Seoul, according to the representative. That incident made headlines in the local media in South Korea, where incidents involving US soldiers often draw attention. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="959" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820275?width=639&amp;height=959" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A photo of Travis King displayed at the home of his grandfather in Kenosha, Wis.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> In October, he was involved in another alleged assault, the representative said. As a part of that incident, he allegedly damaged a police car by kicking it while he was in the back seat, the representative said. In February, he was fined $4,000 for that incident.</p><p> King&#39;s mother told ABC News that she was shocked to hear her son had crossed the border into North Korea. “I can&#39;t see Travis doing anything like that,” said Claudine Gates, who lives in Racine, Wis. Gates couldn&#39;t be reached by The Wall Street Journal, and the court representative declined to comment on legal representation.</p><p> A spokesman for the US Forces Korea declined to comment on whether King had been held in a detention facility on the US base, but former USFK officials said it was likely he was held at Camp Humphreys. USFK oversees the 28,500 American military personnel stationed in South Korea.</p><h3> An &#39;inconvenience&#39; for US</h3><p> Key questions remain unanswered as to how King went from being escorted out of South Korea to entering North Korea, in just a single day. It couldn&#39;t be determined how he got out of the airport terminal and, by Tuesday afternoon, ended up on a tour of the JSA, a site of high-profile summits and a major tourist draw. King then ran into North Korea “willfully and without permission,” a USFK spokesman said on Tuesday.</p><p> Washington may be unable to win King&#39;s release, former US officials and close Pyongyang watchers say. Unlike most North Korean prisoner incidents of the past, King voluntarily entered the country, rather than having been arrested for sneaking across the border or defacing state propaganda.</p><p> As a cavalry scout, King would likely have been familiar with a lot of sensitive military operational information, such as details about the US Command and Control or the priorities of his unit, said Evans Revere, a former senior State Department official. King may have also even been briefed on matters such as how Washington and Seoul assess the military capabilities of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/kim-jong-un">Kim Jong Un</a> &#39;s regime, he added. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="525" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820431?width=700&amp;height=525" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Travis King, in a black shirt and cap, according to Reuters, was among a group of tourists who visited the Demilitarized Zone on Tuesday in Paju, South Korea, before he crossed the border.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: SARAH LESLIE/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “This guy, even though he is fairly low ranking, still has some experience that the North Koreans will be eager to know about,” said Revere, who spent extensive time in South Korea including with the US Air Force.</p><p> The potential information King could share—should he choose to do so—is unlikely to be sensitive intelligence related to war plans or combat-deployment details, Revere added. “But it&#39;s an irritant, an inconvenience and an embarrassment,” he said.</p><p> How North Korea portrays King&#39;s detainment could shed light on what Pyongyang might have planned next, said Rachel Minyoung Lee, a senior analyst for Open Nuclear Network, a research group based in Vienna.</p><p> For prior cases, North Korean state media has taken anywhere from a single day to more than a month to mention American detainees. In many instances, Pyongyang chose to publicize the event in state-media outlets geared for global audiences and held back from reporting the news domestically.</p><p> For King, North Korea could spin his case as an American soldier who grew disenchanted with the US and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/american-says-he-entered-north-korea-illegally-1418544534?tesla=y&amp;mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">wanted to defect for a better life</a> , or state media could stress the “illegal” nature of his crossing the military demarcation line and treat him as a criminal, said Lee, a former senior North Korea analyst for the US government.</p><p> “Much will depend on whether North Korea views it as a good propaganda opportunity,” she said. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="407" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819753?width=700&amp;height=407" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A military check point near the Demilitarized Zone separating the two Koreas.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Jeon Heon-Kyun/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3> Previous Americans held in North Korea</h3><p> At least six US military servicemen have opted to defect to North Korea over the decades, with all but one of them having crossed through the DMZ. Before King, no American soldier had willfully crossed into North Korea in decades.</p><p> In 1965, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/for-a-u-s-soldier-impromptu-trip-to-north-korea-lasted-four-decades-1513350001?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Army sergeant Charles Jenkins</a> deserted his post in South Korea and fled to the North across the DMZ. He was used for propaganda in North Korea, where he was cast as a capitalist villain in films. After spending nearly four decades in North Korea, he surrendered to US military authorities in Japan and was dishonorably discharged from the US military.</p><p> Other Americans have been held captive in North Korea, facing dire humanitarian conditions. Otto Warmbier, an American university student, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/otto-warmbier-american-detainee-released-by-north-korea-has-died-1497905282?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">was detained and imprisoned</a> in North Korea in 2016 for allegedly defacing a political poster while on a tour. Warmbier died in 2017 upon returning to the US with brain damage.</p><p> The last American to have been detained by North Korea was Bruce Byron Lowrance in 2018. Lowrance was deported by the Kim regime after roughly a month of confinement—an unusually brisk turnaround. The move came months after Kim met former President <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/donald-trump">Donald Trump</a> for the first time in Singapore, and ahead of a second nuclear summit with the US in Vietnam where talks abruptly broke down. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="499" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819953?width=700&amp;height=499" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Army sergeant Charles Jenkins arrived in Japan in 2004 after living for nearly four decades in North Korea following his desertion.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Eric Talmadge/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> North Korea does face some risk holding on to King, given his status as an active US soldier. Any personal injury, illness or something worse happening to King under the watch of the Kim regime could trigger a major backlash among the American public, said Ramon Pacheco Pardo, the KF-VUB Korea chair at the Brussels School of Governance.</p><p> “This is not like a missile test, a nuclear test, or an American tourist, American pastor,” Pacheco Pardo said. “You&#39;re talking about someone who serves in the armed forces, and we know how important this is in the US”</p><p> Historically, North Korea has coerced confessions from American captives, forcing them to admit they were spying for the US or confess to crimes they hadn&#39;t committed.</p><p> In prior decades, former Presidents Jimmy Carter and Bill Clinton went to North Korea to negotiate the release of Americans. In return, the Kim regime enjoyed a boost to national prestige while demonstrating its power and ability to compel such high-level visits.</p><p> Seongmin Lee, director of the Korea Desk at the Human Rights Foundation in Seoul, left North Korea a little over a decade ago when he was in his early 20s, and he recalls North Korea&#39;s portrayal <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB124938154079404323?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">of Clinton&#39;s 2009 visit</a> to win the release of two Americans. Lee remembers North Korean state media stressing the two Americans had committed a crime while reinforcing that a former US president had come to Pyongyang to meet Kim Jong Il, North Korea&#39;s then-leader, to offer a personal apology and an in-person greeting.</p><p> “The impression people got is that these high-profile politicians come to Pyongyang to meet the leader because our leader is great,” said Lee.</p><p> Write to Dasl Yoon at <a href="mailto:dasl.yoon@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">dasl.yoon@wsj.com</a> and Timothy W. Martin at <a href="mailto:Timothy.Martin@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Timothy.Martin@wsj.com</a></p><p id="correction" class="correction"><strong>更正和放大</strong><br>Travis King&#39;s identity in a handout photo was reported by Reuters. An earlier version of this article incorrectly attributed it to the Associated Press. (Corrected on July 19)</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Wed, 19 Jul 2023 15:19:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/travis-king-us-soldier-held-in-north-korea-had-been-detained-in-south-korea-4cded529</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/travis-king-us-soldier-held-in-north-korea-had-been-detained-in-south-korea-4cded529<author><![CDATA[Dasl YoonTimothy W. Martin]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>gfx-contrib</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>武装部队</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>特拉维斯·金</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>武装部队</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category></item></channel></rss>